[[File:Jebena Ethiopian coffee pot.jpg|thumb|right|Traditional jebena from central Ethiopia, distinguished from northern Ethiopian and southern Eritrean pots by its spout.]] The '''jebena''' ({{lang-am|ጀበና}} ǧäbäna), is a container used to brew [[coffee]] in the [[Ethiopia]]n and [[Eritrea]]n traditional [[coffee ceremony]].
==Overview== [[File:Jebena in Asmara, Eritrea.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Jebena with various colorful designs for sale in [[Asmara]], Eritrea]] [[File:Coffee_pot_at_eritrean_restaurant.jpg|thumb|left|150px|An Eritrean jebena]] The jebena is usually made of clay and has a neck and pouring spout, and a handle where the neck connects with the base. The jebenas used in Ethiopia commonly have a spout, whereas those utilized in Eritrea usually do not.{{cn|date=August 2015}}
Typically, when the coffee boils up through the jebena's neck, it is poured in and out of another container to cool it. The liquid is then poured back into the jebena until it bubbles up. To pour the coffee from the jebena a filter made from horsehair or other material is placed in the spout of the jebena to prevent the grounds from escaping. In Ethiopia, a small pottery cup called a ''sini'' or ''finjal'' is used to contain the coffee poured from the jebena.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ethiopianrestaurant.com/ethiopian_coffee.html |title=Ethiopian Coffee Ceremony: Jebena and Cini |website=ethiopianrestaurant.com |publisher= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140208053239/http://www.ethiopianrestaurant.com/ethiopian_coffee.html |archive-date=February 8, 2014 |access-date=February 11, 2015}}</ref>
In Ethiopia they use a slightly different variation, theirs having a separate spout lower on the pot for pouring out the coffee. In Eritrea the jebena has only one spout at the top where they pour in the water and grinds and pour out the coffee.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://ineedcoffee.com/coffee-cultures-eritrea-and-ethiopia/|title=Coffee Cultures: Eritrea and Ethiopia - I Need Coffee|date=2015-04-29|work=I Need Coffee|access-date=2018-04-09|language=en-US}}</ref> There is a small restaurant in Ethiopia made in an image of an Ethiopian jebena figure.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ethiopianrestaurant.com/et/addisababa.html |title=Restaurants in Ethiopia: Addis Ababa |website=ethiopianrestaurant.com |publisher= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140208054849/http://www.ethiopianrestaurant.com/et/addisababa.html |archive-date=February 8, 2014 |access-date=February 11, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.crownhoteladdis.com/coffeehouse.php |title=Coffee House (Jebene bet) at the Crown Hotel, Addis Ababa|website=crownhoteladdis.com |publisher= |access-date=February 11, 2015}}</ref> {{clear}}
